Add the following method to your top/first activity:
```
public void providerInstallerCheck(Context context) {
    try {
        // Checking if the ProviderInstaller is installed and updated
        ProviderInstaller.installIfNeeded(context);
        Toast.makeText(context, "Provider installed and updated!", Toast.LENGTH_LONG).show();
    } catch (GooglePlayServicesRepairableException e) {
        /* If the ProviderInstaller is installed but not updated
        A popup asks the user to do a manual update of the Google Play Services
         */
        e.printStackTrace();
        GooglePlayServicesUtil.showErrorNotification(e.getConnectionStatusCode(), context);
        Toast.makeText(context, "Provider it outdated. Please update your Google Play Service"
                , Toast.LENGTH_LONG).show();

    } catch (GooglePlayServicesNotAvailableException e) {
        e.printStackTrace();

        /* If the ProviderInstaller is not installed but not updated
        A popup redirects the user to the Google Play Services page on the Google PlayStore
        and let the user download them.
         */
        Dialog dialog = GooglePlayServicesUtil
                .getErrorDialog(e.errorCode, this,
                        REQUEST_GOOGLE_PLAY_SERVICES_DOWNLOAD);

        dialog.setCancelable(false);
        dialog.show();
    }
}
```

To secure the views in the App, implement one of the three options below:

1. Check for the `MotionEvent.FLAG_WINDOW_IS_OBSCURED` flag in the `onTouch()` handler of the view.

```
mButton = (Button) findViewById(R.id.button);
mButton.setOnTouchListener(new View.OnTouchListener() {
   @Override
   public boolean onTouch(View v, MotionEvent event) {
     // check if the button view is
     // partly or wholly obscured by another visible window above it.
    if ((event.getFlags() & MotionEvent.FLAG_WINDOW_IS_OBSCURED) != 0) {
       if (event.getAction() == MotionEvent.ACTION_UP) {
          // Process the touch on the button
             }
          // Return true to prevent the button from processing the touch.
             return true;
             }
          return false;
        }
    }
);
```

2. Set `filterTouchesWhenObscured` property on the view. This can be done in either the layout's XML file 
or in the Java code as described below:

* In the `layout.xml` file:
```
<Button
   android:id="@+id/button"
   android:layout_width="wrap_content"
   android:layout_height="wrap_content"
   android:text="sample button"
   android:filterTouchesWhenObscured="true"/>
```

* In code:
```
mButton = (Button) findViewById(R.id.button);
mButton.setFilterTouchesWhenObscured(true);
```

3. Create a custom view and override the `onFilterTouchEventForSecurity()` handler:

```
public class CustomButton extends Button {
   public CustomButton(Context context) {
       super(context);
   }

   @Override
   public boolean onFilterTouchEventForSecurity(MotionEvent event) {
       // check if the button view is
       // partly or wholly obscured by another visible window above it.
       if ((event.getFlags() & MotionEvent.FLAG_WINDOW_IS_OBSCURED) != 0) {
           // dispatch the event
           return true;

       }
       // drop the event
       return false;
   }
}
```

