security_findings.recommendation:
The Remediation for [Intent Redirection Vulnerability article](https://support.google.com/faqs/answer/9267555) lists Google's official recommendation.

To avoid rejection from Google Play, implementing either of the options provided below would suffice. However, only implementing Option #1 can still leave the App vulnerable if the vulnerable, private Activity can be invoked from within an exported Activity. Hence, we recommend implementing Option 2 and/or Option 3 for a more secure solution.

Option 1: Make the affected App component, from which the extracted Intent is redirected, private.

If the affected App component does not need to receive Intents from other Apps, you can make that App component private by setting `android:exported="false"` in your Manifest.

Option 2: Ensure that the extracted Intent is from a trustworthy source.

You can verify that the originating Activity can be trusted using methods like `getCallingActivity`. For example: 

```
 // check if the originating Activity is from trusted package
 if (getCallingActivity().getPackageName().equals("trusted package")) {
   Intent intent = getIntent();
   // extract the nested Intent
   Intent forward = (Intent) intent.getParcelableExtra(""intent_key");
   // redirect the nested Intent
   startActivity(forward);
 }
```

Option 3: Ensure that the to be redirected Intent is not harmful.
You should verify that the redirected Intent
 - will not be sent to any of your App’s private components, and
 - will not grant a URI permission to one of your App’s private content providers.

 Apps can check which component will be used to handle the Intent before redirecting it using methods like `resolveActivity`. For example:
```
 Intent intent = getIntent();
 // extract the nested Intent
 Intent forward = (Intent) intent.getParcelableExtra(“key”);
 // get the component name
 ComponentName name = forward.resolveActivity(getPackageManager());
 // check that the package name and class name are as intended
 if (name.getPackageName().equals(“safe_package”) &&
     name.getClassName().equals(“safe_class”)) {
   // redirect the nested Intent
   startActivity(forward);
 }
```
Apps can check whether an Intent grants a URI permission using methods like `getFlags`. For example:

```
 // extract the nested Intent
 Intent forward = (Intent) intent.getParcelableExtra(“key”);
 // get the flags
 int flags = forward.getFlags();
 // check that the nested intent does not grant URI permissions
 if ((flags & Intent.FLAG_GRANT_READ_URI_PERMISSION > 0) ||
     (flags & Intent.FLAG_GRANT_WRITE_URI_PERMISSION > 0) {
   // redirect the nested Intent
   startActivity(forward);
 }
```

