security_findings.description:
Due to an Android OS issue, the task stack of your app is vulnerable to Activity Injection from a 3rd Party Malicious App on the user’s device.
The Malicious App can exploit a vulnerability in the [`startActivities()`API](https://developer.android.com/reference/android/content/Context#startActivities(android.content.Intent[])) and perform a phishing attack on any App installed on the device. 


The vulnerability lies in the implementation of the[`startActivities()`](https://developer.android.com/reference/android/content/Context#startActivities(android.content.Intent[])) API call and was named [StrandHogg2.0]([https://promon.co/strandhogg-2-0/](https://promon.co/strandhogg-2-0/)) by the [researchers](https://promon.co) who discovered this vulnerability. 

The [`startActivities(Intent[] intents)`](https://developer.android.com/reference/android/content/Context#startActivities(android.content.Intent%5B%5D)) API call accepts an array of Intents to be started and is used to start multiple Activities at once.

The Malicious App can pass a specially crafted sequence of Intents to the `startActivities()` API and inject a Malicious Activity to the top of the task stack of the other App.
```
Intent intent1 = new Intent();
Intent intent2 = new Intent();  
Intent intent3 = new Intent();

// An Activity in the Victim App. 
intent1.setClassName(VICTIM_PKG, VICTIM_CLASS);
intent1.addFlags(Intent.FLAG_ACTIVITY_NEW_TASK);

//An Activity in the Malicious app used to execute the Attack. 
intent2.setClass(this, AttackerActivity.class);

//An Activity in the Malicious App to hide the attack
intent3.setClass(this, DeceptionActivity.class);
intent3.addFlags(Intent.FLAG_ACTIVITY_NEW_TASK);

Intent[] intents = new Intent[]{ intent1, intent2, intent3};

startActivities(intents);

```
The attack works as follows:

1. `intent1` is set to an Activity in the victim App. The `FLAG_ACTIVITY_NEW_TASK` flag is used to create the Activity in a new task stack. 
A task is a collection of activities that users interact with when performing a certain job. The Activities are arranged in a stack in the order in which each Activity is opened.

2. `intent2` is set to a Malicious Activity in the Attackers App. 
Due to a bug in `startActivities()`, the Activity set in `intent2` is put in the same task stack as Activity set in `intent1`. `startActivities()` assumes that `intent2` belongs to the same App to which `intent1` belongs. 
This is the root cause of the issue. 

3. Finally, the Activity set in `intent3` is just for deception to hide the attack from the user. If the user clicks on the recent Apps button, the user will still see the correct set of launched Apps. 

4. Now when the user clicks on the icon of the victim App, since the task stack of the victim App already exists, the Activity at the top of the task stack will be displayed which is the Attacker's Activity.  The Attacker's Activity can now display a phishing screen to harvest the user's credentials. Alternatively, the Attacker's App can also trick users into granting sensitive permissions to the Attacker's App. 

This security vulnerability was given CVE ID: CVE-2020-0096. All versions of Android 7 and below are vulnerable to this issue. On May 1, 2020, Google provided a patch for Android 8 and 9 and classified it as critical in this security bulletin: [https://source.android.com/security/bulletin/2020-05-01](https://source.android.com/security/bulletin/2020-05-01).  
Android 10 and 11 are not vulnerable to this issue.

